Blood Pheasant
>A small plump woman with reddish rings around her eyes and a penchant to wear as much crimson clothes as possible

Crotalaria Podborer

Tibetan Blue Bear

I think that you’re worrying too much. Unless it’s obvious that you have strayed off topic then you’re always in a gray area in a story. With logic and reasoning as well as background information you can set up some pretty varied stuff that is still technically in topic.
I would also like to point out that by straying to a different audience accidentally, you still have an audience.
Lastly you’re worrying about things that rely a lot on the reader. Every person in your intended audience is a person with individual thoughts, preferences, likes and dislikes, and most importantly free choice. You can not change how each and every person will react, the best you can do is be reasonable. If something seems like you’re audience will accept it, they probably will.

I’ll use Sherlock Holmes as an example. People fucking adored Sherlock Holmes when it was being published in a magazine. They loved it so much that when the author ended the series with his death people were pissed. The author likely knew that their audience were always waiting for more, yet still decided to kill Holmes by having him tumble down a waterfall. When the entirety of London reads your stories and adores them it’s a shit idea to throw him over a waterfall.
I’m the same vain if it treads a gray line of /hmofa/ your audience probably will accept it, especially considering how there are sometimes periods of time where nothing new comes out.
Finally, remember that writing is also about what you want, not only what the audience wants. If you have something nicely laid out why change it because the audience wants something slightly different. The best books don’t cater to an audiences every desire in narrative direction.
Personally I would read what you’re writing because I think dragons are awesome and not given enough attention.

I'm paraphrasing novelist Howard Fast here

>There's no such thing as writer's block. Plumber's don't have plumber's block, they have a job to do. A page a day is a book a year.

It doesn't matter if what you write is shit, or has to be thrown away because it doesn't fit. Often writing is an exploratory process and you won't realize the idea you were working on was a bad direction until you get it out of your head and on the page. But it's the necessary groundwork to get to better writing.

>>30488940
Inspiration is bullshit, because inspiration is fickle. What you need is discipline, because if you have the discipline to write no matter what you get both the inspiration and the word count.

Waiting on inspiration also plants the false idea that you should only write if you are guaranteed to be writing "good stuff". As I said above you have to the discipline to pursue the false starts, bad chapters, and shitty characters too. Making writing a habit means you don't get married to your bad ideas, because you'll always be writing more to replace them with.

Anonymous Tue 26 May 2020 04:10:59 No.30490713 Report
Quoted By:
>>30488342
Light self-deprecation isn't always corrosive, especially among those who intimate themselves with language. It's just another release valve for stress and pressure that comes out as banter. Don't get troubled over it; it's part and parcel with chan culture, too.

Inspiration doesn't guarantee a writer will enjoy any part of their process except MAYBE the first 10k-20k (or more) words they power through in week 1. That initial burst of enthusiasm, and the hours of ecstasy spent on those first segments of creative rhapsody, are readily divisible by the time spent in revision. With only two eyes on a work, a passion project can become a tick you wish would just glut itself quickly and fuck off. This is why people are hired, even on no-contract gig work, just for editing. Toss a (You) to your writefags; whether it's detailed critique, or a short paragraph of acknowledgement, it helps.

>>30488917
It's a spook. You overcome it by applying your fingers to your keyboard, and become a key-jabbing punchmonkey, until you're back in the weeds, ultimately descending your pages with more momentum than you're backspacing. It's a simple exercise that calls on a little discipline - when you start anything in token measure, you invite the components of muscle memory and mind, that facilitate that activity, to engage. You might need a little hands-on priming with your implements to start yourself. Works for me, but different strokes.

(Suggestion 1) Try to compartmentalize your creative writing and revising mindsets; write new copy first, revise, revise, make notes, new copy, stop at wherever your story stops (the end of a scene, a chapter); backtrack to where revision left off (if it did), look over your notes and highlights, resume revision. (Suggestion 2) Take breaks, go for walks, get a bite to eat, but set times for yourself. You can structure yourself and your free time, and still pants a story if you prefer the act of writing without a hard outline.
